Introduction

Genomic selection refers to selection decisions based on genomic breeding values (GEBV). The GEBV can be computed using two equivalent models following these assumptions:

  1. A model fitting individual SNP effects simultaneously. In this model, GEBV are computed as the sum of the effects of dense genetic markers, across the entire genome, thereby capturing all the quantitative trait loci that contribute to variation in a trait. This method can be referred as Ridge Regression, or SNP-BLUP or RR-BLUP. Relies on the genetic information based on Marker-QTL LD

  2. A model estimating GEBV directly, by using mixed model equations and the covariance among breeding values defined by a genomic relationship matrices (G). Relies on the genetic information based on Marker-Estimated Relationship

Some important concepts:

  • Training population (trn): genotypes and environments used to make predictions.
  • Validation population (tst): group being predicted, or selection candidates
  • Prediction accuracy: correlation between predicted and true values. Can be performed in cross-validation.

Ridge Regression

A traditional linear regression connecting phenotypes (y) and markers (X) can be written using the following notation:

\[y=\beta_0 + X\beta + e\]

where the error is normally distributed as: \(e\sim N(0,\sigma)\)

Traditional linear regression models seek to mimimize the squared error between predicted and actual observations.

\[argmin_\beta\ \sum^n_{i=1} (y_i - \beta_0 -\sum^p_{j=1} \beta_jx_{ij})^2\]

Ridge regression aim to estimate more conservative values for the \(\beta\) weights in a model, and this is true for both frequentist and Bayesian versions of regularization. The extention from traditional to Ridge Regression is made by modifying the loss function (first term of the equation) to include a penalty term for model complexity (second term):

\[argmin_\beta\ \sum^n_{i=1} (y_i - \beta_0 -\sum^p_{j=1} \beta_jx_{ij})^2 + \lambda \sum^p_{j=1}\beta^2_j\]

The second term in the Ridge Regression formula is called shrinkage penalty and is responsible for the regularization. The central question is deciding how stringent the regularization process should be. As the penalty grows, the degree of shrinkage becomes stronger, and eventually all of the \(\beta\) (i.e., marker effects) are shrunk to zero. A model with all regression coefficients close to null values is not desirable, as it does have any power to prediction. However, when this is close to the null value, the penalty term has no effect, and Ridge Regression will produce the least square estimates. Hence, an ideal scheme is one that can selectively shrink the regression coefficients; i.e., markers with small or no effects should be severely penalized, whereas those with larger effects should not be shrunk at all.

The penalty function, in the RR-BLUP, has a specific form and can be represented as: $= 2 p_i (1-p_i) $, where p is the allele frequency.

Below we presented a simple representation of RR-BLUP method.

GBLUP

Genetic markers across the entire genome can be used to measure genetic similarities. Markers estimate proportion of chromosome segments shared by individuals including identification of genes identical by state (IBS). More details about the GBLUP is presented in this link.

Bellow the equation system that need to be solved to compute the GEBV:

\[ \begin{bmatrix} {X'R^{-1}X} & {X'R^{-1}Z} \\ {Z'R^{-1}X} & {Z'R^{-1}Z} + {G^{-1}\lambda} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} {\hat{b}}\\ {\hat{u}} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} {X'R^{-1}y} \\ {Z'R^{-1}y} \end{bmatrix} \]

\[\hat{b} = (X'V^{-1}X)^{-1}XV^{-1}y\]

\[\hat{u} = GZ'V^{-1}(y-X\hat{b})\]

Where the genomic relationship matrix can be computed using:

\[ G= \dfrac{ZZ'}{2 \sum p_i (1-p_i)} = \dfrac{(M-P)(M-P)'}{2 \sum^m_{j=1} p_j (1-p_j)}\]

Below we presented a simple representation of GBLUP method. When compared to the previus RR-BLUP representation,instead of treating marker as predictors, can predict additive values directly as multivariate normal effects. In this case, the markers are used to compute a covariance matrix that is proportional to genomic relationship matrix G.

GBLUP and RR-BLUP are equivalent models

BLUP and RR-BLUP are equivalent models, as presented below:

The use of GBLUP model has some important features that make it widely used in GS:

  • GEBVs can be calculated in the same way as in pedigree-based BLUP, using software and concepts well known in breeding routines
  • In contrast with the penalized regression (RR and LASSO), the dimensions of the genetic effects are reduced from p × p (where p is the number of markers) to n × n (where n is the number of individuals), which is more efficient for computing purposes.
  • More complex models incorporating GxE interactions and multi-trait analysis can be easily included
  • Pedigree and genomic data can be incorporated in the s0-called single step BLUPs

Hands-on

Demo 1 – RRBLUP vs GBLUP simulated Data

Mice data set

  • Same approach reported by de los Campos here
  • Select only 5000 markers in the mice genome
  • Simulate a phenotype with h2=0.5 controled by 10 QTLs (quantitative trait)
  • Objectives:
    • Fit Ridge Regression and GBLUP model using the rrBLUP package.
    • Estimate the marker effects
    • Prediction via RR-BLUP
    • RR-BLUP vs GBLUP

R code

# Data Simulation
library(BGLR)         # R package where we will download the data
set.seed(12345)
data(mice) 
n<-nrow(mice.X)       # 1814 phenotypes
p<-ncol(mice.X)       # 10346 markers
mrkSet<-sort(sample(1:p,size=5000))              # select 5000 markers
X<-scale(mice.X[,mrkSet],center=TRUE,scale=TRUE) # scale the data

# ---- Toy simulation example ----
# i) Simulating 10 QTL in the genome
set.seed(12345)
nQTL<-10 ; p<-ncol(X); n<-nrow(X) ; h2<-0.5 # number of QTL and h2
whichQTL<-sample(1:p,size=nQTL)             # position the QTL
b0<-rep(0,p)                                # empty vector
b0[whichQTL]<-rnorm(n=nQTL, mean=3,sd=1)    # QTL ~ N(3,1)
plot(b0)

# ii) Creating the effects  
signal<-as.vector(X%*%b0)                   # marker * effect
SD<-sqrt(h2/var(signal))                    # scaling the effect
b0<-b0*SD ; signal<-signal*SD
plot(b0)
error<-rnorm(n,sd=sqrt(1-h2))               # random error
var(signal)/var(signal+ error)              # checing if the h2 =0.5

# iii) Simulating the phenotypes (genetic + error)
y<-signal+error                            # Xb+e 

# iv) Fitting RRBLUP model
library(rrBLUP)
fit1 <- mixed.solve(y = y, Z = X) # RR-BLUP
gebv = X %*% fit1$u ## GEBV
plot(fit1$u,ylim=range(b0),col=1,ylab='Estimate')
points(x=whichQTL,y=b0[whichQTL],col=2)
abline(v=whichQTL,col=8)

# v) Fitting a GBLUP model
G = A.mat(X)
fit2 <- mixed.solve(y = y, K = G) 

# vi) Some results
plot(fit2$u,gebv) # rrBLUP vs. GBLUP
cor(y,fit2$u) # Accuracy in the TRN data set

# vii) Accuracy in TST data set
# 500 first individuals --> TST
y_tst = y[1:500]
x_tst = X[1:500,]

y_trn = y[-c(1:500)]
x_trn = X[-c(1:500),]

fit3 <- mixed.solve(y = y_trn, Z = x_trn) # RR-BLUP
gebv_trn = x_trn %*% fit3$u ## GEBV
gebv_tst = x_tst %*% fit3$u ## GEBV

cor(gebv_trn,y_trn)
cor(gebv_tst,y_tst)

plot(gebv_trn,y_trn,pch=20, main="TRN and TST prediction")
points(x=gebv_tst,y=y_tst,col=2, pch=20)

Additional questions

We simulated 5 QTLs with different \(h^2\) values:

  2. Why the estimated and simulated \(\beta\) values are very different?

Demo 2 – Wheat data set

  • Example used in class
  • wheat.Y = phenotypic data
  • wheat.X = genotypic data
library(BGLR)
library(rrBLUP)

# Download the data
data(wheat)
dim(wheat.A)
dim(wheat.X)
dim(wheat.Y)

# Fit RRBLUP
fit1 <- mixed.solve(y = wheat.Y[,2], Z = wheat.X) # RR-BLUP
gebv = wheat.X %*% fit1$u ## GEBV
cor(gebv,wheat.Y[,1])
plot(abs(fit1$u))

# Fit GBLUP
G =A.mat(wheat.X)
fit2 <- mixed.solve(y = wheat.Y[,1], K = G) # GBLUP
cor(fit2$u,wheat.Y[,1])
plot(gebv, fit2$u, main = "RR-BLUP vs. GBLUP")
fit2$Vu/(fit2$Ve+fit2$Vu) # h2

# Accuracy in TST data set
y_tst = wheat.Y[1:100,1]
x_tst = wheat.X[1:100,]

y_trn = wheat.Y[-c(1:100),1]
x_trn = wheat.X[-c(1:100),]

fit4 <- mixed.solve(y = y_trn, Z = x_trn) # RR-BLUP
gebv_tst = x_tst %*% fit4$u ## GEBV
cor(gebv_tst,y_tst)

Demo 3 – Cross-validation

How good is my model to perform predictions based only on genomic data? To solve this practical question we use cross-validation. There are different scenarios of cross-validation. The most common sampling phenotypic values from only one part of the data set (called the training set), fitting a prediction model and predicting for the rest (called test data set). In short:

  • TRN data set: genomic + phenotypic = predictive model
  • TST data set: predictive model + genomic = predictions

By breaking the data in traning and test data sets, we can have an unbiased estimate of model’s prediction accuracy. The most common metric to evaluate the predictive performance is the Person’s correlation between phenotype and genomic estimated breeding value.

There are different flavors for cross-validation. k-fold cross-validation means is one of the most popular in the GS literature. Below, we have an example of 3-fold cross-validation. For that, the data are split in 3 folds of approximately equal population size, and information from each fold is used once for test while the others are used as training. In this format, a total of 3 GS models are fitted.

Example of 3-fold cross-validation. Steps: i) Collect the phenotypic and genotypic data in 12 portions; ii) Shuffle the data; iii) Split in 3 folds; iv) Fit a genomic prediction model using the train data and predict the phenotype in the test

R codes from 10-fold cross-validation

library(BGLR)
library(rrBLUP)
data(wheat)
dim(wheat.Y)
dim(wheat.X)
x = wheat.X
y = wheat.Y[,1]

# i) Creating the fold
n=559                               # original number of individuals
k=10                                # how many folds/partitions
set.seed(123)                       # same fold/partitions division every time
folds=sample(1:k,size=n,replace=T)  # creating random partitions 
folds                               # ind assigned to diff folds
table(folds)  

# Fitting Genomic selection using 10-fold CV scheme
r2 = vector()                        # empty vector to save the accuracy values

for(i in 1:max(folds)){              # loop across the folds
  print(i)
  # ii. Creating the test data set (individuals that we will predict)
  test = which(folds==i)
  y_train=y[-test]
  y_test = y[test]

  x_train= x[-test,]
  x_test= x[test,]
               
  # iii. Fitting the model in the Training data set
  fit = mixed.solve(y_train, x_train)
  
  # iv. Prediction in the test
  yhat = x_test %*% fit$u
  
  # vi. Pearson's correlaction
  r2[i] = cor(yhat, y_test,use="complete")
}

boxplot(r2)

Demo 4 – Shiny app

ShinyGPAS is an interactive genomic prediction accuracy simulator based on deterministic formulas. Deterministic formulas for the accuracy of genomic predictions highlight the relationships among prediction accuracy and potential factors influencing prediction accuracy prior to performing computationally intensive cross-validation. Visualizing such deterministic formulas in an interactive manner may lead to a better understanding of how genetic factors control prediction accuracy. App was originally published by Morota, 2017. Here, I’m using the app to demonstrate how the predictive ability is modified as some parameters are changed. In the literature, there are different equations available.
